{
  "doc_id": "1972",
  "text": "Electrocardiographic imaging accurately identifies areas of anatomic scar and complements standard anatomic imaging by providing scar-related EP characteristics of low voltages, altered SR activation, electrogram fragmentation, and presence of late potentials. Delayed enhanced magnetic resonance imaging (DE-MRI) has been used to noninvasively identify anatomic myocardial scars in patients with prior myocardial infarction (MI) [CITATION_1] . DE-MRI has been used to improve prediction of ventricular arrhythmia inducibility at electrophysiology study [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] , and of spontaneous ventricular arrhythmia and mortality [CITATION_4] .",
